<dl id="n54143i"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n54" href="#n54143i">N54 (VI.B.45)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n54all.htm#n54143i"> 143(i)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> painting ochres <small>Orange</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n54143i"><li>FW 27.05 </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/lexa.htm#n54143i">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/a/l39a.htm#n54143i">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n54143i">MS BL 47476b-469</ms> </li><li>JJA 50:275 <a name="ad8" href="../../FF/fdra/ada.htm#ad8">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/a/ad8.htm#n54143i">Draft: I.1&sect;1.8</a>/2.8</li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">Pour se pr&eacute;parer &agrave; l&apos;attaque, les guerriers <mark>se peignaient</mark> sur le corps des serpents, des traces d&apos;ours, ou des mains d&apos;homme, <mark>avec de l&apos;ocre rouge</mark>, de l&apos;argile blanche ou du charbon. <br><font color="green">[To prepare for the attack, the warriors painted themselves on the bodies of snakes, bear tracks, or human hands, with red ocher, white clay or coal.]</font> <small> Lucian L&eacute;vy-Bruhl, <a name="LBEM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#LBEM"><cite title="source">L'exp&eacute;rience mystique</cite></a> (1938) 180</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
